<TITLE> Stocks close down for a second day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 15 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks closed lower for the second straight day Tuesday with shares in banks, power, insurance and mutual funds diving on sell-offs. "Investors Tuesday were selling off to gain profits. There were also rumours of something very bad happening like a massive fall in share prices," said a top official of broker house, preferring anonymity. Dhaka Stock Exchange chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed however said rebalancing of portfolios by investors led to the selling spree to cash in. "The turnover board for the last two days had a lot of other companies. Usually it's dominated by banks. It indicates that investors are willing to change their portfolios," he said. The market started with a fall in the general index, which started to gain after the second hour of trading. It remained somewhat stable in the midday sessions before falling again toward the end. The benchmark DGEN or general index closed 7.44 points or 0.25 percent down to 2931.78. The DSI or all share price index shed 5.31 points or 0.21 percent to end at 2478.93. The DSE-20 blue chip index closed at 2429.36, down 1.6 points or 0.06 percent. Turnover on the country's prime bourse stood at Tk 1.56 billion from trading of 8,332,737 shares. Gainers beat losers 133 to 90 while 17 issues held steady. AB Bank topped the turnover board; it fell 1.84 percent to Tk 2782.75. State-run Jamuna Oil, however, gained slightly to Tk 300, up 0.03 percent, after it debuted the previous week. Power heavyweight Summit Power slumped 4.02 percent to Tk 1447.25. Grameen Mutual Fund One eroded Monday's gains and fell 1.04 percent to close at Tk 85.10. IFIC bank also declined 1.48 percent to end at Tk 2788.25. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, BRAC Bank, Square Pharma and Prime Bank also lost. NBL and Fareast Life Insurance gained. Bengal Biscuit, Raspit Inc, Meghna Shrimp, German Bangla Food and Meghna Life Insurance were among the major gainers. Amam Sea Foods, Padma Oil Company, sixth ICB Mutual Fund, ICB AMCL 1st Mutual Fund and National Tubes topped the losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended lower. The CSCX or selective categories index declined 13.46 points or 0.27 percent to 4870.15. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7587.44, down 16.87 points or 0.22 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 index closed 15.69 points or 0.22 percent lower to 6873.25. Turnover totalled Tk 162.670 million from trading of 2,676,281 shares. Of the issues traded, 58 advanced, 66 declined and nine remained unchanged. bdn
